{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472645","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472645"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1554"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1554"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.06,0.01,0.09,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1554"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111780"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1554"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1554"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93850"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"825"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6186"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41703"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111780"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-month-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. Her parents have no specific concerns. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her head circumference is tracking above the 97th centile, while her weight and length are both on the 60th centile. She is developmentally appropriate, having met all milestones to date. The anterior fontanelle is soft and not bulging. Apart from the large head circumference, the examination is otherwise normal. A cranial ultrasound reveals no abnormalities. Her mother mentions that her older sister also had a large head when she was younger.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate follow-up management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Regular monitoring of head circumference","Magnetic resonance imaging of the brain","Electroencephalogram to assess for seizure activity","Genetic karyotype analysis","Neurosurgical consultation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a child with familial macrocephaly, which is a benign condition characterised by an enlarged head circumference without associated neurological abnormalities. The diagnosis is supported by the child\u0027s normal development, absence of neurological symptoms, normal examination (apart from the large head), normal cranial ultrasound, and family history of large head size.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular monitoring of head circumference\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate follow-up management for familial macrocephaly. This involves measuring the head circumference at routine well-child visits to ensure that growth continues along a consistent percentile curve. Developmental monitoring is also important, but this would be part of routine care rather than a specific intervention. As familial macrocephaly is benign, no specific interventions are required beyond this monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnetic resonance imaging of the brain\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if there were concerns about increased intracranial pressure, developmental delays, or neurological symptoms. In this case, with normal development, normal examination, normal cranial ultrasound, and a family history of large head size, an MRI is not necessary and would expose the child to unnecessary sedation risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectroencephalogram to assess for seizure activity\u003C/strong\u003E would only be indicated if there were concerns about seizures or abnormal neurological findings. There is no mention of seizure activity or neurological abnormalities in this case, making an EEG unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic karyotype analysis\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered if there were dysmorphic features, developmental delays, or other signs suggesting a genetic syndrome. In isolated familial macrocephaly without other abnormalities, genetic testing is not routinely indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurosurgical consultation\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were signs of increased intracranial pressure, abnormal neurological findings, or imaging abnormalities suggesting hydrocephalus or other structural issues requiring surgical intervention. None of these are present in this case, making neurosurgical consultation unnecessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Macrocephaly is defined as a head circumference greater than the 97th centile on growth charts.","Familial macrocephaly is a benign condition characterised by an enlarged head circumference without associated neurological abnormalities.","Regular monitoring of head circumference is the appropriate follow-up for children with familial macrocephaly to ensure growth remains proportional."],"references":["Flett, P., \u0026 Russo, R. (2012) Neural tube defects, large heads and hydrocephalus. In South, M. \u0026 Isaacs, D. (Eds) Practical Paediatrics (pp613 \u2013 624).Edinburgh: Churchill Livingstone/ Elsevier.","Johnson, D., \u0026 Wilkie, A. (2011). Craniosynostosis. European Journal Of Human Genetics, 19(4), 369-376. doi: 10.1038/ejhg.2010.235"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93850"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1554"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19958"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19958"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ec5162e8-792b-4330-a794-05cf87c93081.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ec5162e8-792b-4330-a794-05cf87c93081.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":448,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93850"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-19T19:32:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T19:34:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1554"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111780"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups"